Twitter=E2=80=99s Link Ban
------------------

It was another crazy weekend at Twitter; Elon Musk, as I write this, is run=
ning a poll ( https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1604617643973124097 ) ask=
ing if he should step down as head of Twitter, and that he promises to abid=
e by the results. If Musk=E2=80=99s past polls are any indication there is =
a good chance he has already made the decision; for the record, I voted =E2=
=80=9CYes=E2=80=9D (which just won 57.5% to 42.5%).

To that end, we spent an hour on Sharp Tech talking about everything that h=
as gone down with Musk and Twitter over the past few weeks, from the Twitte=
r Files to the media reaction to last week=E2=80=99s suspensions; the episo=
de will come out later today and, given just how many threads there are to =
this story, I really think a podcast was the best way to articulate my thou=
ghts on the matter. As always you can add Sharp Tech to your podcast player=
 using the link at the bottom of this email; I=E2=80=99ll include a link to=
 the episode in tomorrow=E2=80=99s email.

The one topic I did want to address in the Update is the since-rolled back =
ban on links to other social networks. From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloombe=
rg.com/news/articles/2022-12-18/twitter-will-remove-accounts-that-link-to-o=
ther-social-media ) :

Twitter said it will remove accounts =E2=80=9Ccreated solely=E2=80=9D to pr=
omote other social media platforms. The company =E2=80=9Cwill remove accoun=
ts created solely for the purpose of promoting other social platforms and c=
ontent that contains links or usernames=E2=80=9D for Facebook, Instagram, M=
astodon, Truth Social, Tribel, Nostr and Post, Twitter Support said in a se=
ries of tweets Sunday.

The reaction to this move was probably the most unanimous condemnation of M=
usk yet, including prominent members of the tech industry; Paul Graham was =
amongst those condemning the change in a tweet ( https://twitter.com/paulg/=
status/1604556563338887168 ) , for which his account was promptly suspended=
.

Twitter can, of course, do what it wants: it is a private company. I recogn=
ize that is an unsatisfactory answer, but perhaps the degree to which it ha=
s always been unsatisfactory will now resonate more broadly. An extension o=
f this argument is to point out that powers once cheered become feared when=
 in the hands of those with whom you disagree, so it is worth weighing whet=
her such powers ought ever be developed or sanctioned in the first place. A=
gain, though, these are all better topics for a podcast, at least until we =
reach a resolution to this saga.

Network Portability
-------------------

What I do want to highlight is that while this particular implementation ap=
peared to be a crude regex run against the text of tweets and bios, it=E2=
=80=99s not the first time that Twitter has acted to limit would-be competi=
tors. From TechCrunch ( https://techcrunch.com/2012/07/26/no-api-for-you-tw=
itter-shuts-off-find-friends-feature-for-instagram/ ) in 2012:

Instagram has just announced 80 million users and a new app update; Noticea=
bly missing in the update? The =E2=80=9CFind Your Friends=E2=80=9D on Twitt=
er feature, which allowed users to follow the same people they follow on Tw=
itter on Instagram. The =E2=80=9CTweet Photo=E2=80=9D feature is still avai=
lable. We=E2=80=99ve learned that the feature is missing due to API restric=
tions from Twitter=E2=80=99s end, restrictions that possibly came about ove=
r concerns about Instagram=E2=80=99s scale and its strain on data pulls.

Those aren=E2=80=99t the reasons Twitter cut off Instagram=E2=80=99s API ac=
cess; the real issue is that Instagram bootstrapped its social network on t=
he back of Twitter. While the photo sharing service started as way to add f=
ilters to photos you shared to other social networks, the real prize was in=
 building a network, and the easiest way to do that was to import your Twit=
ter contacts. Unfortunately for Twitter 80 million people were already on b=
oard before the company acted, and Instagram didn=E2=80=99t really need Twi=
tter anymore, soon zooming past the primarily text-based social network in =
active users.

The folks that Instagram=E2=80=99s API access were good for =E2=80=94 beyon=
d Instagram=E2=80=99s founders, investors, and eventually Facebook =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0were users who could replicate their social network on a new servi=
ce. To that end, imagine if new Twitter rivals could rely on more than scra=
ping the bios of people you follow to look for links to other social networ=
ks: what if Twitter=E2=80=99s API still included access to your friend grap=
h? It would still be hard to build a Twitter competitor, but it would be a =
whole lot easier than it is currently; Twitter, though, along with every ot=
her social network, learned its lesson and shut down API access to your fri=
end graph.

You might think that this would be an opportunity for government regulation=
, and, in theory, you would be right: if every social network had to make y=
our friend graph API accessible it would be far more viable to build altern=
ative social networks. From The Web=E2=80=99s Missing Interoperability ( ht=
