Much of the discussion around a potential invasion of Taiwan =E2=80=94 whic=
h would destroy TSMC (foundries don=E2=80=99t do well in wars) =E2=80=94 ce=
nters around TSMC=E2=80=99s lead in high-end chips. That lead is real, but =
Intel, for all of its struggles, is only 3~5 years behind. That is a meanin=
gful difference in terms of the processors used in smartphones, high perfor=
mance computing, and AI, but the U.S. is still in the game. What would be m=
uch more difficult to replace are, paradoxically, trailing node chips, made=
 in fabs that Intel long ago abandoned. China meanwhile, has had good reaso=
n to keep TSMC around, even as it built up its own trailing edge fabs: the =
country needs cutting edge chips, and TSMC makes them. However, if those ch=
ips are cut off, then what use is TSMC to China?

The U.S. has a massive strategic weakness when it comes to trailing edge ch=
ips: TSMC is the only alternative to China (beyond Global Foundries=E2=80=
=99 relatively small capacity), which means if TSMC goes away China has a s=
tranglehold on the chips that are most used in daily life; that fast chip i=
n your smartphone or PC doesn=E2=80=99t help you drive your car or operate =
your industrial robot or manage your appliances. To that end, it makes perf=
ect sense for China to double down on the trailing edge: not only does this=
 weaken TSMC (by driving down prices on its cash cow long-since-depreciated=
 foundries), it also gives China leverage over the United States.

To that end, this is why I have argued that the CHIPS Act should have been =
focused on building trailing edge capacity: it=E2=80=99s relatively cheap, =
but there is no economic case for a private entity to build new-old fabs; t=
he reason to build new ones is strategic, which is where government subsidi=
es could help, but unfortunately no one is lobbying/threatening lawmakers l=
ike, say, an Intel, which already has all of the motivation it needs to bui=
ld new cutting edge fabs with or without subsidies.

